Sure! Here's a C++ code that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int countWordOccurrences(const std::string& filename, const std::string& word) {
    std::ifstream file(filename);
    std::string line;
    int count = 0;

    if (file.is_open()) {
        while (std::getline(file, line)) {
            size_t pos = line.find(word);
            while (pos != std::string::npos) {
                count++;
                pos = line.find(word, pos + word.length());
            }
        }
        file.close();
    } else {
        std::cerr << "Cannot open file: " << filename << std::endl;
    }

    return count;
}

int main() {
    std::string filename, word;
    std::cout << "Enter the filename: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, filename);
    std::cout << "Enter the word to count: ";
    std::cin >> word;

    int occurrences = countWordOccurrences(filename, word);
    std::cout << "The word \"" << word << "\" occurs " << occurrences << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, the `countWordOccurrences` function takes two parameters, `filename` (the name of the text file to read) and `word` (the specific word to count occurrences). Inside the function, we open the file, read it line by line, and count the occurrences of the word using the `find` function.

In the `main` function, we get the filename and word from the user, then call the `countWordOccurrences` function to get the count of occurrences. Finally, we output the result to the console.

Please make sure to include error handling for file opening and closing, as shown in the code.
